We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
Direct the MT to maintain a cash book for CAs granted to her name and conduct regular reconciliation of records with the accounting;
To evaluate the possibility of bonding qualified personnel who actually utilize the CAs granted to stop the practice of transferring cash advance from one accountable officer to another.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
Continue its compliance with the mandatory provision for the collection of biodegradables, recyclables, non-recyclables and special/hazardous wastes;
Institute additional measures to fully enforce the Municipal-wide observation of wastes diversion strategies to include source reduction, recycling and composting;
Continue the proper maintenance of the Central MRF and enjoin all the Barangay personnel to strictly adhere to the prescribed guidelines on the establishment and maintenance of MRF; and
Ensure compliance to the pertinent provisions in the RA 9003 applicable to the Local Government Unit.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to direct:

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer to  comply with Section 114, Volume I of the NGAS Manual which is to record Inventories under the perpetual inventory method and to maintain their respective supplies/stock/property ledgers and cards;
The Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of Inventories as required under Section 124, Volume I  of the same Manual;
The Municipal Accountant, the Municipal GSO, and the Municipal Engineer to comply with Sections VI and VII of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommend the following:

Prepare a Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP)  as mandated by COA Circular # 2012-002;
Evaluate the agency’s capability in responding calamity. Procure the best suited basic rescue and response equipment depending on the nature of disaster usually occurs in the locality. Reference may be had  with  DILG Memorandum Circular #2012-73  for the type of disaster and the type of equipment;
Organize , train, equip and supervise the Local emergency response teams and Accredited Community Disaster Volunteers (ACDVs) , ensuring that humanitarian aid workers are equipped with basic skills to assist mothers to breastfeed;
Develop, strengthen and operationalize mechanism for partnership or networking with private sectors, Civil Society Organizations (CSOs) and volunteer groups. 
Maintain a database of human resource , equipment, directories, and location of critical infrastructures and their capacity such as hospitals and evacuation centers;
Display hazard maps on prominent places.
All Equipment and other facilities acquired for rescue operation should be booked up as “Disaster Response and Rescue equipment” as required under item 5.1.7 of COA Circular # 2012-002.
Undertake programs, projects or activities consistent with the provision of Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Plan.

We recommend the following:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Assessor in establishing the accurate amount of basic RPT and SET receivable from each taxpayer as of the end  2014; 
 Prepare an entries to adjust the amount of recorded receivable to reconcile the general ledger balance with the amount actually collectible from each taxpayer based on the certified list of collectibles and reflected in the taxpayer’s ledgers; 
Require the Accounting Office to set and maintain updated index card for each taxpayer to facilitate the establishment of the accurate amount of collectible from each taxpayer; and
 Direct the Municipal Treasurer to invariably furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers and the actual amount due and collectible for the year as basis in setting up the Real Property tax and Special Education Tax receivable for the year.

